lewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Gwenllian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>gwen</i>, the feminine form of <i>gwyn</i> ‘white, fair; blessed, holy’ (  see  Gwen  ) + <i>lliant</i> ‘flood, flow’ (probably in the transferred sense ‘foamy’ or ‘white’, referring to a pale complexion)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwenllian ferch Llywelyn was born in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Llywelyn ap Cynwrig and Efa ferch Gwion. She had at least 1 daughter with Ithell Anwyl."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1470":"1470","{Lln Eurdorchog}":"Leelanau, Michigan, Ameerika Ühendriigid","of Bryn Hwfa,Llys-y-cil,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1470":"1470","{Lln Eurdorchog}":"Leelanau, Michigan, Yhdysvallat","of Bryn Hwfa,Llys-y-cil,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt